Objectives

Even if you havent coded in R before, going to try to briefly acquaint you with some new, cool data science techniques. From zero to data science hero!

Motivating example: eDNA Shiny app

Shiny is an R package and framework for building interactive applications. It provides a set of functions for building a front end web interface (into a file ui.R) that gets updated based on a back end set of R custom rendering functions (server.R). Well be diving into this more later. You can also get quick gander at the geyser eruption example on the homepage shiny.rstudio.com.

Shiny represents the end point, or motivating use case, for today to interactively visualize your data, after cleaning it up using data wrangling techniques. Heres an example of a Shiny app for environmental DNA (eDNA) data:

ecoquants.shinyapps.io/edna-vis

Heres the code for this app:

  • github.com/marinebon/edna-vis

Note that the app is hosted at Github.com, the online versioning portal where the open source world collaboratively codes. As is this little tutorial:

  • github.com/marinebon/r4edna

Note how the code repository view of docs/index.html gets served as an actual web page to this URL:

  • marinebon.github.io/r4edna

This is according to conventions laid out by Github Pages, or serving up free websites from files stored on Github. All content on Github is organized according to owner/repository. (Notice how they get rearranged between github.com and github.io.)

Youll also notice this document is generated with Rmarkdown, a document format for rendering chunks of R code with plain text formatted (headers, bold, links, etc) using the markdown style (which gets automatically rendered in Github).

Phyloseq

Collin Closek provided this file in Biological Observation Matrix format (*.biom).

To read this, well use the R package phyloseq.

Install phyloseq

source('http://bioconductor.org/biocLite.R')
biocLite('phyloseq')
  • Importing phyloseq Data

Read *.biom file

# load libraries
library(phyloseq)

# set working directory to Rmd so same as Knit
if (basename(getwd()) != 'docs') setwd('docs')

biom = '../data/MB_json_obs_md.biom'

p = import_biom(biom)
p
## phyloseq-class experiment-level object
## otu_table()   OTU Table:         [ 452 taxa and 63 samples ]
## sample_data() Sample Data:       [ 63 samples by 61 sample variables ]
## tax_table()   Taxonomy Table:    [ 452 taxa by 7 taxonomic ranks ]

Plot bar

plot_bar(p)

Plot tree

plot_tree(p)
Error in plot_tree(p) : 
  There is no phylogenetic tree in the object you have provided.
